<TEXT>
territorial conflicts that brought about the 
war between iran and iraq eight years ago will jeopardize the truce 
that both countries have accepted an iranian specialist in 
international law said monday 
a 1975 border treaty could be the solution and for iran there 
should be no questions said alireza deyihim deputy dean of 
irans diplomatic academy that is affiliated with the foreign 
ministry 
he said in an interview that both countries had accepted the 
1975 pact and iraq clearly violated international law when it 
abrogated the treaty unilaterally in 1979 
iraq invaded iran in september 1980 after a series of border 
skirmishes 
iran and iraq agreed monday to accept the united nationss call 
for a ceasefire un security council resolution 598 also states 
that both iraqi and iranian forces should withdraw to the 
internationally recognized borders without delay after the 
ceasefire is in place 
deyihim said iran believes that phrase means the forces should 
withdraw to the borders agreed upon in the 1975 treaty between iraq 
and irans government of shah mohammed reza pahlevi that was 
overthrown in 1979 in the revolt led by ayatollah ruhollah khomeini 
both countries have ratified this treaty and announced 
ratification to the united nations deyihim said that treaty 
settled all problems including the border in the shattalarab 
the 120mile waterway that flows into the persian gulf and forms 
the southern border between the warring neighbors 
deyihim who entered irans foreign service 17 years ago and was 
involved in the 1975 treaty negotiations said if iraq had wanted 
to renegotiate parts of the agreement it could have used the 
complaints procedure that is part of the pact 
he claimed iraq had removed many of about 570 markers set to 
delineate the 730mile border after the 1975 treaty 
they removed them and even pulled out trees that marked 
the border he said 
we hope that this border issue does not cause a delay in 
implementing the ceasefire he added 
</TEXT>
