<DOCNO> AP880808-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
japans doors are hesitantly open to a trickle of 
americans seeking an experimental antiaids drug that has not been 
approved for use in the united states 
the drug dextran sulfate was developed in japan in the 1960s 
and has been used to treat arteriosclerosis and high cholesterol 
within the last year however japanese and american researchers 
have shown in the test tube that the compound is a potent agent 
against infection by hiv which causes the fatal acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome 
now researchers are trying to determine whether dextran sulfate 
is effective when given to aids patients and whether they can take 
large doses over a long period 
the drugs potential has received wide publicity and some 
american aids sufferers or their friends have sought the drug in 
japan 
a year ago i started receiving calls from american guys who 
asked if dextran sulfate was available said manabu yamamoto 
manager at the american pharmacy in central tokyo i had no idea 
it could be used against aids 
now yamamoto says two or three americans come in every month 
seeking dextran sulfate 
the american pharmacy is one of three pharmacies in the tokyo 
area that were authorized two months ago to sell the compound under 
tight control but without a doctors prescription by the 
phamarceutical division of kowa co ltd one of about a dozen 
makers of dextran sulfate in japan 
we talked it over with the ministry of health and decided for 
humanitarian reasons it would be sold to american tourists said 
kowa spokesman kazuhiro endo 
endo said the company limited overthecounter sales to three 
pharmacies because if dextran sulfate were widely available it 
would be difficult to give proper warnings to purchasers there 
could be damage and we as a pharmaceutical company are quite 
worried about this he said 
a buyer at the american pharmacy must sign a form in english 
stating how many tablets were purchased that they were for 
personal use that the drug is approved in japan for treatment of 
high cholesterol at a dosage of 450900 milligrams a day and that 
it affects blood coagulation and should not be used by hemophiliacs 
a separate page includes information on adverse reactions such 
as skin eruptions anorexia and diarrhea 
the dosages being considered for aids therapy are much higher 
than routine use in japan we dont have any information on this 
drug in such high dosage endo said adding that if a patient 
takes a high dosage the risks might be higher 
he declined to name all three pharmacies permitted to sell the 
drug though he said their names were wellknown to san francicso 
aids sufferers he said kowa was concerned that people that people 
with irrational fears of aids might experiment with dangerously 
high doses 
the three pharmacies reportedly have anywhere from two to 30 
customers per month 
the company also worries that buyers might start a black market 
business exporting the drug which sells at the american pharmacy 
for 272 for 1000 300milligram tablets 
kowa is not doing aids research with dextran sulfate japans 
leader in that area is a 70yearold chemical firm ueno fine 
chemicals which has no medicines currently on the market 
ueno is worried that its research backed in the united states 
by the national institute of health may be harmed by personal 
imports by american aids sufferers 
from a humane point of view we will not do anything to stop 
the drugs sale to americans said dr ryuji ueno director of the 
department of medicine at his familys company we are just a 
little disappointed though 
at stake for the company is the possibility of a lucrative us 
market if the drug is proved effective 
the us food and drug administration recently reaffirmed its 
policy of letting aids patients import drugs for their personal use 
even if they have not been approved 
but the fda last week ordered inspectors to block imports of 
dextran sulfate from polydex pharmaceuticals ltd of toronto 
canada saying the canadian company was promoting its unproven drug 
in violation of federal rules 
the fda has approved clinical tests of uenos dextran sulfate 
compound but approval for use of the drug in aids therapy still is 
a long way off ueno said in a telephone interview from his 
laboratory near osaka so far he said the drug has been tested 
for side effects on patients at san francisco general hospital 
the current phase of tests which began july 7 involves giving 
patients increasingly higher doses to see whether the drug is 
effective against hiv and to determine its side effects ueno said 
the research is being done at nine aidstreatment centers in the 
united states and will take six months 
ueno said the fda had granted his compound open drug status 
meaning authorities will help fund research and give the drug a 
protected market for seven years if it is successful 
japan has had only 80 aids cases according to the ministry of 
health and welfare so few that the drug could not be tested on 
patients 
aids is most often transmitted through sexual contact other 
means of transmission include transfusions of tainted blood or 
blood products and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles 
or syringes by drug abusers aids can also be passed from mother to 
child at or before birth 
</TEXT>
