<TEXT>
elephants at the beijing zoo have forgotten the 
taste of bananas and tigers are now rarely thrown a live chicken 
hard times have befallen their keepers 
the official china daily said today that the 3000 animals 
birds and fish at chinas largest zoo have come across lean days 
because of inadequate funding and sharp rises in food prices 
with the quadrupling of banana prices in recent years elephants 
have been put on a diet of nutritious but less palatable carrots 
zoo officials said 
tigers now get just two meals a day down from three and are 
fasting one day a week zoo officials said explaining that the big 
cats are used to eating irregularly in the wild 
in addition tigers lions and other carnivores that used to 
have a twiceweekly treat of a live chicken or rabbit now feast on 
such delicacies only when they are sick or weak 
the report said the zoo had to give away its most popular seal 
because it couldnt afford the annual expense of up to 13500 in 
fish 
we dont want to adopt these cruel measures but as our budget 
is tightened there seems to be no other way around the report 
quoted jiang hongtao office director of the zoo as saying 
the daily said expenses at the zoo have shot up from 11 
million in 1984 to 19 million last year 
the state last year provided 810000 and the zoo had to make 
up the rest by introducing video games bumper cars and other 
sources of recreation admission to the zoo costs less than a 
nickel 
the zoos chief accountant yang qingchuan said expenses may 
double next year because of swiftly rising food costs 
consumer prices rose 19 percent in june compared to the same 
month in 1987 while prices of some food items have nearly doubled 
in the past year with the elimination of some government price 
controls 
the zoo opened in 1908 and is home to rare animals such as the 
giant panda and the golden monkey it is one of the capitals main 
tourist attractions 
</TEXT>
