<TEXT>
tropical storm beryl the second named storm of the 
atlantic hurricane season hugged the louisiana coast today 
forcing evacuations from oil rigs in the gulf of mexico while the 
seasons first tropical storm fizzled out near the canadian coast 
beryl was upgraded today from a tropical depression after its 
winds strengthened reaching close to 45 mph with gusts up to 55 
mph the storm strengthened as it drifted closer to the warm waters 
of the gulf of mexico oil companies evacuated more than 2000 
workers from oil rigs in southern louisiana and the gulf 
the tropical storm had a center near latitude 295 north and 
longitude 893 west it was drifting southeastward at less than 5 
mph and its movement was expected to be slow and erratic through 
tuesday the storms center was about 50 miles southeast of new 
orleans 
there is some likelihood it could strengthen said mark 
zimmer of the national hurricane center in miami its not 
drifting inland its drifting away from land but very slowly 
zimmer said the immediate danger from beryl was to shipping and 
oil rigs along the gulf coast people on the coast he said should 
watch for tides of up to three feet above normal 
tropical storm warnings were in effect from morgan city la to 
pensacola fla and small craft from port oconnor texas 
eastward to appalachicola fla should remain in port the center 
said 
right now were advising people to listen to their radios and 
watch television said andy valence mayor of grand isle la 
about 40 miles south of new orleans in the gulf of mexico 
its highly unusual for depressions to form over land most of 
the time they get their start way out in the middle of the ocean 
said jim gross a forecaster at the national hurricane center in 
miami we dont have a lot of experience with systems that form 
this way 
a tropical weather system becomes a named storm when its winds 
hit 39 mph and a hurricane when wind velocity reaches 74 mph 
the storm chiefly affected those out on oil rigs in the gulf 
the weather service said 
chevron spokesman jonathan lifa said about 2000 workers were 
being evacuated early today all employees at facilities at venice 
and leesville in plaquemines parish were evacuated by boat and 
helicopter while nonessential personnel were removed from a 
facility at morgan city 
lifa said the storm became more threatening as it neared the 
gulf 
news reports over the weekend were that the center was 
partially onshore and partially offshore so we didnt have high 
winds to worry about lifa said the concern is that the more 
it gets into the gulf the more winds pick up it is something we 
are very concerned about 
texaco spokesman max hebert said an unknown number of workers 
were taken off texaco rigs in the gulf of mexico today 
coast guard petty officer first class bob morehead said the 
coast guard has not carried out any evacuations but the storms 
winds buffeted helicopters and created choppy seas for its ships 
the storm didnt appear to affect republicans gathering in new 
orleans for their national convention next week about 2 percent 
or 105 of the delegates have arrived to serve on various 
preconvention panels and committees said connie thumma 
codirector of media operations for the convention 
better this week than next week said bill phillips the 
convention manager 
