<TEXT>
detroit will be among 20 cities in which two 
newspapers have combined some of their operations to keep one of 
the publications alive according to the american newspaper 
publishers association 
the joint operating agreement between the detroit free press and 
the detroit news approved monday by the justice department is the 
fifth approved under the newspaper preservation act 
the law enacted in 1970 allows a limited antitrust exemption 
to preserve independent editorial voices in a community where one 
newspaper is in danger of failing 
many agreements that had joined the operations of newspapers in 
other cities before the law was enacted were grandfathered under 
the act and allowed to continue in effect said terry maguire anpa 
senior vice president and general counsel those pre1970 
agreements had been reached by the newspapers themselves without 
need of any government action 
previous agreements approved under the newspaper preservation 
act involved newspapers anchorage alaska in 1974 cincinnati in 
1979 chattanooga tenn in 1980 and seattle in 1982 
the anchorage agreement later was dissolved 
according to maguire other joint operating agreements 
grandfathered under the act and still in effect involve newspapers 
in albuquerque nm el paso texas nashville tenn evansville 
ind tuscon ariz tulsa okla fort wayne ind birmingham 
ala salt lake city shreveport la knoxville tenn charleston 
wva pittsburgh honolulu san francisco and miami 
other agreements grandfathered under the law but were later 
dissolved included those between newspapers in oil city and 
franklin pa st louis and columbus ohio he said 
