<TEXT>
the house approved legislation monday to 
prohibit political contributions for state and local campaigns from 
being used for a federal race a step critics say amounts to 
protection for members of congress 
the bill was sent to the senate by voice vote 
however several members disputed criticism voiced by fred 
wertheimer president of the selfdescribed citizens lobby common 
cause 
current election law permits some money raised for state or 
local races to be used in a campaign for congress so long as the 
candidate did not violate any federal restrictions on the sources 
or amounts of contributions 
in a letter last week to house members wertheimer said that 
with the proposed law incumbent members of congress would be 
making it far more difficult for a state or local official to 
challenge a sitting member of congress 
members of congress could continue as they now do to raise 
reelection campaign funds throughout their term while preventing 
challengers from using any money that may have been raised prior to 
declaring for federal office even though that money meets 
contribution limits in federal law he wrote 
wertheimer noted that the bill by rep bill thomas rcalif 
does not provide a similar prohibition on house members using 
money raised for house races to run for the senate 
the bills floor manager rep al swift dwash said the 
proposal is intended to close a loophole in campaign law 
created by a ruling by the federal elections commission 
swift said the ruling for example allows a state official to 
use contributions from corporations illegal for federal offices 
to cover some expenses connected with raising money for a 
congressional race 
wertheimer also criticized swift and other members of the house 
administration committee for failing to produce a single piece of 
meaningful campaign finance reform legislation in recent years 
swift said however that the panel wont propose any major 
reform package until the senate first passes one senate democrats 
ran into paralyzing republican filibusters in 1987 and 1988 when 
they tried to move a bill setting up spending limits for senate 
races 
</TEXT>
