<TEXT>
scott bakula took on a broadway musical right 
after he went into a primetime television series with the 
understanding that it would be goodbye new york if the tv show 
turned into a hit 
instead eisenhower amp lutz was canceled by cbs and romance 
romance a modest little musical that uses only four actors and 
minimal scenery has blossomed on broadway 
the timing was incredible bakula said the other day 
sitting in his dressing room at the helen hayes theater we 
wrapped the series in midfebruary and started rehearsals for 
romance romance in march 
i came into it saying ive got a tv series and may have to 
go back in midjune he recalls and the producers said 
ok 
romance romance two separate oneact musicals looks at 
love in two very different places turnofthecentury vienna and 
trendy modernday east hampton long island 
bakula plays a rakish man about town in the first act and an 
anguished yuppie contemplating an affair with a friends wife in 
the second 
the show and bakula were nominated for 1988 tony awards neither 
won but the musical received national exposure on the tony 
telecast and has found a growing audience a recording by mca 
classics is scheduled for release in late summer 
for bakula the recognition secured a stage reputation that 
sprouted before he first went off to california to do television 
the 33yearold bakula is one of those actors who looks at ease 
in both mediums although he says he is more comfortable on stage 
than on television 
i find the camera to be confining but ive gotten over 
that he says i tend to like to be physical on stage to move 
and to do things 
television requires a certain precision he says hitting your 
mark and then being still 
how can you act bakula asks but thats the trick of it 
when youre coming from the theater now im used to it 
bakula who hails from st louis found performing a part of his 
life while growing up 
i always sang and that led to doing theater he says he 
went to the univerity of kansas to study business but later 
switched to theater 
i left school and came here to work in 1976 not study 
theater bakula recalls but i ended up studying my head off 
all over town for years 
still bakula had a job in show business the third day he was in 
new york although he had to leave town again to get it the work 
was in a dinner theater in north carolina which was doing 
shenandoah a musical that supported him a lot during his first 
years in new york 
whenever times got lean it seemed like a company of 
shenandoah would come up he says 
the actor finally made it to broadway in 1983 seven years after 
arriving in new york he survived marilyn an american fable a 
shortlived and muchmaligned musical based on the life of marilyn 
monroe in it he played new york yankee legend joe dimaggio one 
of monroes husbands 
the troubled show which had 13 producers listed above the 
title went through weeks of previews after the first director 
choreographer and leading lady were replaced 
it was very frustrating bakula says now but it was my 
first broadway show so it also was very exciting 
the experience led bakula almost immediately into a much happier 
effort 3 guys naked from the waist down the offbroadway 
musical written by michael rupert and jerry colker was a hip 
offbeat look at the world of standup comedians one job in show 
business bakula had never tried 
now i know why people are standup comics he says when 
you are really cooking you feel like you can stay out there for 
two hours and theyll laugh at anything you say its a real heady 
kind of feeling to be totally in control of an audience 
bakula went west to appear in a los angeles production of the 
offbroadway musical nite club confidential he moved into 
television with an occasional role on cbs designing women as 
annie potts exhusband and a major part in abcs gung ho 
which died quickly in a brutal time slot where it faced both 
dallas and miami vice 
bakula was cast as the flybynight lawyer in eisenhower amp 
lutz in july 1987 but the first episode wasnt filmed until 
october cbs didnt require a pilot because of the sterling 
reputation of the shows producers alan burns and mtm 
the 13 episodes that eventually were made didnt set the 
nielsens afire though the ratings had started to improve when the 
show was canceled 
i cant really explain what cbs did to the show he says 
we did everything they asked of us we even got the 18 to 
40yearold audience that sponsors love 
the network only has six halfhour shows on the schedule for 
the fall he adds there were not that many slots to fill 
