<TEXT>
a mama bear is a crowdpleaser 
especially with a rolypoly cub romping at her side but whats a 
zoo to do when baby grows up 
too often surplus penreared black bears are sold traded to 
dubious buyers or killed and the mother bred again so zoo visitors 
wont be robbed of the baby bear experience said michael pelton a 
wildlife science professor 
pelton of the university of tennessee and doug scott of the 
tennessee wildlife resources agency are tracking radiocollared 
bears released from zoo areas into the cherokee national forest 
penraised black bears have been used in research in tennessee 
but this is the first time weve made a concerted effort to keep 
track of them pelton said we want to learn more about how 
they react to a new environment after having been born in 
captivity 
the main thrust of the study is to determine simply if these 
animals will make it in the wild and if theyre suitable for 
release scott said thats the big question should we even 
take these bears off the hands of zoos or should we just allow 
them to be bought and sold 
six bears wearing radio collars have been released three each 
from the ober gatlinburg and grandfather mountain resort zoos one 
bear grew dependent on area residents for ice cream and other food 
handouts when the zoo that had housed it declined to take it back 
the bear had to be killed the resort later relented and took back 
another bear after similar problems arose scott said 
a third bear was found dead in the forest foul play is 
suspected and an autopsy is pending radio contact has been lost 
with a fourth bear 
despite the problems neither pelton nor scott is ready to give 
up 
about 20 penraised black bears have been released into the wild 
in tennessee over the last 10 to 15 years but without radio 
collars theres no way of knowing their whereabouts pelton said 
in the past tattoos and ear tags were used on penraised bears 
at least three have turned up dead as the result of legal hunts 
which tells researchers they managed to adapt at least to nature 
the handling of bears in captivity has a lot to do with their 
odds of making it in the wild pelton said often theyre fed 
dried dog food rather than berries and acorns and are given treats 
by zoo visitors neither practice boosts their chances of adapting 
in addition their cages are sometimes bereft of places to climb 
and hide a more natural environment and theyre allowed too much 
contact with humans 
several years ago the state prohibited the caging of tennessee 
black bears in areas other than bona fide zoos or zoological parks 
the law doesnt require special diets or cages to help the bears 
survive in the wild if the need arose 
my hope is that the state game people say to the people who 
