<TEXT>
the edwin p hubble space telescope is 
to float next year from a space shuttle beyond the haze of 
atmosphere to let scientists peer into the depths of the universe 
and 14 billion years into the past 
it should see seven times as far as the most powerful 
earthbound scopes 
originally scheduled for august 1986 launch it so far hasnt 
looked at anything it sits wrapped in silvery thermal blankets 
running up bills 
beyond 15 billion to build it the cost of work during the 30 
months of delay since the challenger explosion will reach 400 
million nasa says faulty devices have driven up costs by as much 
as 10 million a year 
thats for a project envisioned in 1977 as costing 572 million 
the telescope must be protected from even minute amounts of 
dust moisture and noise in the clean room giant fans cleanse 
the air through filters that can screen particles 200 times thinner 
than a hair 
the 42foottall spacecraft has been taken apart and almost put 
back together in preparation for shipping in november to cape 
canaveral scientific instruments designed to be serviced every 
three to five years in space have been out more than a dozen times 
for inspections repairs and improvements 
meanwhile budgetminded officials arent the only ones 
concerned about the delay so are astronomers and the european 
space agency which paid 15 percent of the building costs and 
provided a sophisticated faint object camera 
data from the hubble was to be the centerpiece of the 
international astronomical unions 1988 meeting scheduled five 
years ago and held last week in baltimore the goddard space flight 
center in nearby greenbelt md is managing the instruments 
mission operations and data 
the hubble named for an american astronomer who provided the 
first proof of others than our milky way is smaller than many 
landbased telescopes but should give sharper images because it 
will be 350 miles above the atmosphere 
astronomers will look for evidence of planets in other solar 
systems study planets in our solar system in more detail search 
for black holes and measure the distance between stars more 
accurately they will try too for a better understanding of the 
origins and possible fate of the universe 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
baby should have his first checkup 
some experts believe about five months before birth 
all women should have careful ultrasound in the fourth month 
of pregnancy as though it is the babys first physical exam said 
dr judith g hall of the university of british columbia 
most people think about prenatal diagnosis as preparatory to 
early termination of the pregnancy said hall but really its 
not it allows us to begin early treatment 
in ultrasound the echoes of sound waves make pictures of the 
fetus 
about 5 percent of babies have significant congenital 
malformations physical defects present at birth that require 
extensive treatment or change a childs life while the newborn 
death rate has fallen dramatically over the years the liklihood of 
serious birth defects has not changed 
hall contends at least half of all these birth defects could be 
spotted before birth through ultrasound exams among other things 
she said it can be used to check the severity of osteogenesis 
imperfecta a birth defect in which the child suffers broken bones 
the scan can help determine whether the child would benefit from 
caesarean section to avoid fractures during birth 
ultrasound can also help spot fetal heart block in which the 
fetus heart fails to beat strongly enough this can be treated 
before birth 
dr beryl r benacerraf a radiologist at harvard medical 
school said a major study sponsored by the national institutes of 
health is trying to find if routinely doing the more sophisticated 
ultrasound is worth the expense between 150 and 300 but even if 
it turns out to make economic and medical sense on a large scale 
it will not immediately be available everywhere 
