<TEXT>
terry holsapples rather unconventional 
approach to farming began with a simple observation one crop can 
help another crop grow 
when we plowed down a crop of alfalfa we had the best corn 
ever said holsapple i had been taught to use all these 
chemicals that really gets you to thinking 
so holsapple decided five years ago to abandon chemically 
intensive agriculture and experiment with plants like hairy vetch 
and rye they control weeds add nutrients and organic matter to 
the soil and protect the land from erosion the natural way he 
said 
the yields have not suffered in fact they might have picked 
up a hair said holsapple who now raises corn and soybeans with 
fewer commercial fertilizers and pesticides thats money in your 
pocket 
holsapple 33 recently showed other interested farmers some of 
the techniques successful and unsuccessful that he uses on his 
400acre farm in cumberland county 
it is one of 14 farms across the nation cooperating in 
experiments sponsored by the rodale institute of emmanus pa a 
nonprofit group doing research on regenerative agriculture 
we need to diversify crops and methods stop soil erosion and 
rely less on fossil fuels said ken mcnamara rodales midwest 
research coordinator the systems we develop here will be around 
for our children and our grandchildren 
during a wagon tour of his farm holsapple offered some pointers 
fallplanted hairy vetch can be turned under the soil in the 
spring to supply nitrogen for corn eliminating the need for that 
fertilizer in commercial form 
these cover crops dont let weeds get started in the spring 
said holsapple that vetch will even smother out horseweed 
a field of tall lush corn was cultivated to kill weeds and 
grasses before they got a good start herbicides are a last resort 
youve got to have a rotary hoe or you might as well throw up 
your hands and go to town said holsapple who paid 15 for a 
small used one at a sale if that doesnt work you can always 
come back and spray later 
a field of dead vetch and little corn demonstrated the problem 
of planting the grain into the vetch without plowing during a dry 
year the vetch sucked all the moisture out and the corn didnt 
germinate 
holsapple also experiments with spring peas as a cover crop to 
provide nitrogen for corn 
he raises melons and other produce in small irrigated fields to 
sell locally 
he produces his own seed for vetch rye and soybeans buying 
only commercial hybrid corn seed 
and he adds fertilizers only when a soil test indicates it will 
be cost effective 
we just keep trying things said holsapple the more i do 
this the more enthused i get 
