<TEXT>
labor secretary ann mclaughlin announced a 
148 million plan monday to meet the emergency survival needs of 
thousands of migrant and seasonal farm workers left without money 
or jobs because of the drought 
but rep albert bustamante dtexas said the labor departments 
package is not enough to help migrant workers stranded across the 
droughtparched midwest without a job or enough money to finance 
the return trip home 
when youre looking at the amount of money big farmers 
agriconglomerates are getting they really are not providing for 
the bottomrung people who do the harvesting and stoop labor 
bustamante said 
they should have been more fair in trying to bring relief to 
these people said bustamante himself a former migrant worker 
bustamante said he had sought 20 million to 25 million which 
would have come closer to meeting shortterm survival needs 
a 39 billion package of drought assistance for farmers 
ranchers and dairy producers passed the senate on monday and could 
receive final legislative approval as early as tuesday in the house 
bustamante said he was working with house majority whip tony 
coelho dcalif and house agriculture committee chairman e 
kika de la garza to free up more money for the migrant workers 
mrs mclaughlin promised the labor department would marshal 
funds quickly she said she also was writing to state governors and 
agencies to recommend special employment services and 
unemployment insurance consideration for migrant farm workers 
the severe drought in some parts of the nation has had a 
devastating effect on migrant farm workers and their families 
mrs mclaughlin said in a statement some are stranded without 
work or money to return home while others face extreme hardship at 
their home base 
mrs mclaughlin said she has authorized existing migrant worker 
programs operating under labor department grants to use up to 15 
percent of their current funding for emergency services such as 
health care transportation and temporary shelter the agency said 
that could mean up to 95 million may be spent 
she said another 5 million has been set aside from a job 
partnership training act reserve account for displaced workers to 
be used specifically for migrant farm workers hurt by the drought 
the labor department also said portions of some states may be 
declared disaster areas triggering a disaster unemployment 
insurance program 
twentytwo states have asked the department of agriculture to be 
designated droughtdisaster areas these states have an estimated 
200000 migrant and seasonal farm workers the labor department 
said 
they are alabama delaware idaho illinois indiana iowa 
kentucky maryland michigan minnesota missouri montana new 
jersey north dakota ohio pennsylvania south dakota tennessee 
texas west virginia wisconsin and wyoming 
