<TEXT>
the detroit news and detroit free press will 
be allowed to merge their business and production operations 
because the smaller free press was in danger of financial failure 
stemming from years of steady and apparently irreversible losses 
attorney general edwin meese iii said monday 
in approving the application for a joint operating agreement 
meese rejected the recommendation of a justice department 
administrative law judge who said the two newspapers pricing 
policies were unrealistic 
meese however said there was little prospect for the free 
press to return to profitability in detroits highly competitive 
market 
for me the continuing and persistent operating losses 
suffered by the free press over the course of nearly a decade with 
no prospect of unilaterally reversing that economic condition in 
the foreseeable future describes a newspaper in danger of 
financial failure meese said in his opinion 
meese told reporters that the free press losses were not 
manipulated but came from intense competition 
the detroit joint operating agreement was the fifth approved by 
the justice department under the newspaper preservation act of 
1970 which allows limited antitrust exemption to preserve 
independent editorial voices in a community where one newspaper is 
in danger of failing 
previous partial mergers were approved for newspapers in 
anchorage alaska in 1974 cincinnati in 1979 chattanooga tenn 
in 1980 and seattle in 1982 
the free press owned by knightridder inc and the news owned 
by gannett co inc had asked permission in may 1986 to merge 
their advertising circulation and production operations under a 
law designed to preserve newspaper competition 
the newspapers which rank among the nations 10 largest said 
the free press was in danger of going out of business without the 
joint operating agreement knightridders directors had voted to 
shut down the free press if the justice department had rejected the 
application for a joint operating agreement 
knightridder said in january that the free press operating 
losses had totaled 100 million since 1979 and that the news had 
lost about 75 million in the same period the free press lost 18 
million on revenues of 172 million in 1987 
this decision reaffirms the will of the congress that two 
independent editorial voices should be preserved wherever possible 
in the cities of america alvah h chapman jr knightridder 
chairman said in a statement issued in miami 
free press publisher david lawrence said this is the best 
single day of my years at the free press it leads the way to the 
next century of service for the free press which already has been 
part of michigan for more than a century and a half 
gannett chairman allen neuharth and president john j curley 
also expressed gratification 
we said all along that the joa was the only way to preserve 
two independent news and editorial voices they said in a 
statement issued from gannett headquarters in suburban arlington 
va the attorney generals decision is in the best interest of 
the community the readers the advertisers and the employees 
said jerry w friedheim president of the american newspaper 
publishers association while the administrative law judge in the 
detroit case misapplied the statute in some important ways we are 
pleased that the attorney general appears to have taken a view more 
consistent with the intent of congress 
a justice department administrative law judge morton needelman 
recommended in december 1987 that meese deny the request on grounds 
that the newspapers losses were due to unrealistic circulation and 
advertising discounts aimed at forcing each other out of business 
the newspapers denied needelmans assertion saying he lacked an 
understanding of the newspaper business 
bruce mcintyre publisher of the oakland press one of several 
suburban detroit papers that had criticized the joint operating 
agreement request said he was quite surprised that meese had 
ignore the advice of the judge who had heard all the evidence in 
the case and made a very studious decision 
while meese was still considering the case free press editor 
joe stroud rejected three cartoons about meese by staff cartoonist 
bill day another knightridder paper the miami herald also 
decided not to publish editorial cartoons about meese while the 
case was pending 
newspaper employee unions and detroit mayor coleman young 
initially opposed the partial merger but most dropped their 
opposition after knightridder directors voted to shut down the 
free press if they failed to win approval of a joint operating 
agreement 
meese said the owners threat to close the free press was noted 
in the record of the case but was not the deciding factor in his 
decision 
the newspaper guild the last employee union to oppose the joint 
operating agreement dropped its opposition july 25 
michigan gov james blanchard and most of the michigan 
congressional delegation supported the agreement 
the free press had circulation in march of 647763 daily and 
721676 on sundays the 10th largest circulation in the nation 
according to the audit bureau of circulation the circulation of 
the news was 688211 daily and 836331 on sundays the eighth 
largest nationally the bureau said 
the free press was founded in 1831 and purchased by a 
predecessor of knightridder in 1940 the news was founded in 1873 
and purchased by gannett in 1986 
</TEXT>
