<TEXT>
the nations biggest airline company texas air corp reported 
monday that its secondquarter net loss widened sharply while 
trans world airlines inc said its profit after taxes nearly 
doubled 
houstonbased texas air said its net loss widened to 2559 
million from a loss of 27 million in the second quarter of 1987 
the company blamed a significant part of the loss on government 
investigations of alleged safety problems at its two main 
subsidiaries continental airlines and eastern airlines 
texas airs secondquarter revenue slipped 14 percent to 213 
billion from 216 billion a year earlier 
the department of transportation and the federal aviation 
administration launched investigations of eastern and continental 
in midapril that were unprecedented in their scope the probes 
which continued for most of the second quarter concluded that both 
airlines were being run safely 
however a federal report concluded that labor turmoil at 
miamibased eastern must be defused before it creates risks to 
passengers 
texas air said monday the investigations cost eastern and 
houstonbased continental a total of more than 60 million in lost 
revenue and 14 million in expenses such as overtime advertising 
and legal and accounting fees 
both airlines have implemented various marketing and service 
programs to counter the effects of these investigations on consumer 
confidence but the companies have continued to experience some 
revenue losses beyond the second quarter due to them texas air 
said in a press statement 
at eastern the secondquarter net loss was 898 million 
compared with net income of 271 million a year earlier easterns 
revenue in the most recent quarter declined to 1 billion from 12 
billion 
continental posted a 199 million loss before a 131 million 
adjustment associated with a reestimation of its air traffic 
liability the adjustment had been announced earlier and had no 
impact on continentals cash position texas air said 
including the adjustment continental lost 1509 million on 
revenue of 11 billion in the second quarter in the same period a 
year earlier the airline lost 711 million on revenue of 1 
billion 
the results in the latest quarter brought texas airs net loss 
for the first half of the year to 3801 million widened from a 
loss of 1277 million in the first six months of 1987 
texas airs firsthalf revenue rose 14 percent to 426 
billion from 420 billion 
new yorkbased twa said its net profit almost doubled in the 
second quarter from a year earlier largely due to a cash payment 
it received from a lawsuit against its former owner the late 
howard hughes 
the nations seventhlargest airline said its net income jumped 
to 972 million or 270 a share from 528 million or 128 a 
share in the second quarter of 1987 
in addition to a 499 million gain from the hughes lawsuit twa 
said its earnings also benefitted in the quarter from cost 
controls a rebound in international passenger traffic which had 
been hurt by fears of terrorism and the longterm advantages of 
twas merger with ozark air lines 
twas secondquarter revenue rose 86 percent to 114 billion 
from 105 billion a year earlier 
profit in the latest quarter includes the 499 million gain 
from a cash judgment awarded to twa in 1987 in its longstanding 
lawsuit against hughes the twa managements suit originally filed 
in 1962 alleged that the eccentric multimillionaire failed to 
provide the carrier with adequate aircraft 
although a delaware court decided in twas favor last year the 
payment was not made until the second quarter 
in the first half of the year twa earned 447 million or 50 
cents a share compared with a net loss of 2 million in the first 
six months of 1987 
firsthalf revenue increased 96 percent to 206 billion from 
188 billion 
