<TEXT>
a federal judge ruled monday that the tiny south 
pacific island republic of palau must pay an international 
consortium of banks more than 44 million on defaulted loans 
the republic a 200island archipelago in the south central 
pacific ocean about 600 miles east of the philippines borrowed 
more than 30 million to build an electric power generating station 
in the early 1980s 
the nation once a us trust territory in march defaulted on 
the loans and the consortium that had guaranteed the loans had to 
pay them off the banks sued the country population 14200 for 
repayment 
under the decision the banks morgan guaranty trust morgan 
grenfell amp co ltd bank of tokyo ltd bank of scotland and 
orion royal bank ltd are entitled to collect some 443 million 
in unpaid loans capitalized interest insurance premiums fees and 
expenses 
in his 57page opinion us district judge robert w sweet said 
the case presented an involved factual matrix and complicated 
issues of sovereignty and commercial law arising out of the 
struggle of the unsophisticated island people of palau to achieve 
independence both economic and political 
but the judge concluded the banks were entitled to collect the 
amounts they had guaranteed 
sweets ruling was the latest round in a threeyear legal battle 
between the banks some of the largest in the world and palau 
whose main industry is fishing 
this decision is but one step along what may turn out to be a 
long road but at least this phase has been completed said sweet 
after a weeklong trial in april and final arguments in june 
sweet ruled that palau willingly waived its right to sovereign 
immunity and thus protection from lawsuits when it signed the 
loan agreements sweet also ruled that palau failed to prove its 
contention that the banks had misrepresented how the power plant 
would pay for itself or that palauan officials signed documents 
they did not understand 
</TEXT>
